                <p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;</p>
                <p style="text-align: justify;">A safety factor must be used when calculating the temperature of dust-air mixture and dust layers. For a dust-air mixture, the safety margin is calculated by multiplying the ignition temperature of the mixture by 0.67. When the dust layer thickness exceeds 5 mm, the safety margin is calculated by deducting 75 Kelvin from the maximum tested temperature causing a dust explosion in the atmosphere.</p>
                <p><img style="display: block; margin: 0 auto; width: 554px;" src="/images/upload/atex4.png"></p>
                <p style="text-align: justify;">The ignition properties of the dust present must be known when evaluating dust atmospheres. <em>T.ign-cl</em> is the lowest surface temperature required to ignite a dust cloud. <em>T.ign-lay</em> is the lowest surface temperature required to ignite a dust layer and <em>E.min</em> is the lowest electric spark energy capable of igniting the most flammable dust-air mixture.</p>
                <p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Examples of the ignition properties of dusts</strong></p>
